# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bearing-mechanical
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] Materials include M50 tool steel (AMS6491), carbon chrome steel (AMS6444), the corrosion resistant AMS5930, 440C stainless steel, silicon nitride (ceramic) and titanium carbide-coated 440C.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] Typically, special attention is given to the material specification, non-destructive testing, and to the traceability of the bearing (a system of documents that enables an engineer to trace a bearing, typically back to its manufacturing batch and material supply).
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] In order to assure bearing performance, it is necessary for the bearing steel to be of high quality.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] Jet engine bearings are typically manufactured from metals manufactured using a vacuum arc remelt to enable material requirements to be met.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] Jet engine shaft bearings and accessory drive shaft bearings typically use single piece or two piece machined retainers.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] The pressed steel or moulded retainers found on mass-produced bearings are not used.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] Temperature and moisture resistant oils, greases and lubricants are normally specified.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] If the lubricant is not correct the performance of the bearing will be compromised.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] In jet engines bearings can operate at over 200 degrees Celsius (400 °F) and at speeds over 10,000 rpm for the turbine shafts to over 30,000 rpm in the accessory drives.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] In wing control surface applications temperatures as low as −55 °C (−67 °F) may be encountered.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] Bearings are a vital factor in many products and assemblies and their performance is often monitored continuously.
[src:bearing-mechanical/aerospace-bearings] In jet engines the oil supply is monitored to detect the presence of metallic debris that could identify a failure either of the bearings or of other components whose failure may contaminate the bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/agostino-ramelli] Ramelli was born in Ponte Tresa or Mesanzena, today in Switzerland.
[src:bearing-mechanical/agostino-ramelli] During the Siege of La Rochelle (1572–1573), he successfully engineered a mine under a bastion and breached the fortification, making him popular with his commander, Henri d'Anjou, who later became King Henri III of France.
[src:bearing-mechanical/agostino-ramelli] In 1588, Ramelli published *Le diverse et artificiose machine del Capitano Agostino Ramelli*, or *The various and ingenious machines of Captain Agostino Ramelli*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/agostino-ramelli] The book contains 195 designs, over 100 of which are water-raising machines, such as water pumps or wells.
[src:bearing-mechanical/agostino-ramelli] Other designs include bridges, mills, and a possible forerunner to the Wankel engine.
[src:bearing-mechanical/agostino-ramelli] Some of his pump mechanisms feature early rotary and multi-piston concepts that conceptually resemble modern axial piston pumps (for example, those used today in car air conditioning compressors).
[src:bearing-mechanical/agostino-ramelli] The bookwheel is one of the most famous designs from this book.
[src:bearing-mechanical/agostino-ramelli] *Le diverse et artificiose machine* is still printed and sold.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] A differentiation is made between aerodynamic bearings, which establish the air cushion through the relative motion between static and moving parts, and aerostatic bearings, in which the pressure is being externally inserted.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Gas bearings are mainly used in precision machinery tools (measuring and processing machines) and high-speed machines (spindle, small-scale turbomachinery, precision gyroscopes).
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Hybrid bearings combining the two families also exist.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In such cases, a bearing is typically fed with externally-compressed gas at low speed and then relies partially or entirely on the self-pressurizing effect at higher speeds.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Pressurized gas acts as a lubricant in the gap between moving parts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The gas cushion carries the load without any contact between the moving parts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Normally, the compressed gas is supplied by a compressor.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] A key goal of supplying the gas pressure in the gap is that the stiffness and damping of the gas cushion reaches the highest possible level.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In addition, gas consumption and uniformity of gas supply into the gap are crucial for the behaviors of aerostatic bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] There is no single best approach to feeding the film.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] All methods have their advantages and disadvantages specific to each application.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] With conventional single-nozzle aerostatic bearings, the compressed air flows through a few relatively large nozzles (diameter 0.1 – 0.5 mm) into the bearing gap.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The gas consumption thus allows only some flexibility such that the bearing's features (force, moments, bearing surface, bearing gap height, damping) can be adjusted only insufficiently.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] However, in order to allow a uniform gas pressure even with few nozzles, aerostatic bearing manufacturers take constructive techniques.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In doing so, these bearings cause dead volumes (non-compressible and thus weak air volume).
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In effect, this dead volume is very harmful for the gas bearing's dynamic and causes self-excited vibrations.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The pre-pressured chamber consists of a chamber around the centralized nozzle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Usually, this chamber's ratio is between 3% and 20% of the bearing's surface.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Even with a chamber depth of 1/100 mm, the dead volume is very high.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In the worst cases, these air bearings consist of a concave bearing surface instead of a chamber.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Disadvantages of these air bearings include a very poor tilt stiffness.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Typically, conventional aerostatic bearings are implemented with chambers and canals.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] This design assumes that with a limited amount of nozzles, the dead volume should decrease while distributing the gas within the gap uniformly.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Most constructive ideas refer to special canal structures.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Since the late 1980s, aerostatic bearings with micro-canal structures without chambers are manufactured.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] However, this technique also has to manage problems with dead volume.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] With an increasing gap height, the micro-canal's load and stiffness decreases.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] As in the case of high-speed linear drives or high-frequency spindles, this may cause serious disadvantages.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Laser-drilled micro-nozzle aerostatic bearings make use of computerized manufacturing and design techniques to optimize performance and efficiency.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] This technology allows manufacturers more flexibility in manufacturing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In turn this allows a larger design envelope in which to optimize their designs for a given application.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In many cases engineers can create air bearings that approach the theoretical limit of performance.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Rather than a few large nozzles, aerostatic bearings with many micro-nozzles avoid dynamically disadvantageous dead volumes.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Dead volumes refer to all cavities in which gas cannot be compressed during decrease of the gap.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] These appear as weak gas pressure stimulates vibration.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Micro-nozzle aerostatic bearings achieve an effective, nearly perfect pressure distribution within the gap with a large number of micro-nozzles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Their typical diameter is between 0.02 mm and 0.06 mm.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The narrowest cross-section of these nozzles lies exactly at the bearing's surface.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Thereby the technology avoids a dead volume on the supporting air bearing's surface and within the area of the air supplying nozzles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The micro-nozzles are automatically drilled with a laser beam that provides top-quality and repeatability.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The physical behaviors of the air bearings prove to have a low variation for large as well as for small production volumes.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In contrast to conventional bearings, with this technique the air bearings require no manual or costly manufacturing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Some of these advantages, such as the high flexibility, the excellent static and dynamic properties in combination, and a low noise excitation, prove to be unique among all other aerostatic bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Gas-lubricated bearings are usually modeled using the Reynolds equation to describe the evolution of pressure in the thin film domain.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Unlike liquid-lubricated bearings, the gas lubricant has to be considered as compressible, leading to a non-linear differential equation to be solved.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Numerical methods such as Finite difference method or Finite element method are common for the discretization and the resolution of the equation, accounting for the boundary conditions associated to each bearing geometry (linear-motion, journal and thrust bearings).
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In most cases, the gas film can be considered as isothermal and respecting the ideal gas law, leading to a simplification of the Reynolds equation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Even for movements which cause damage due to disruptive wear with roller bearings, lifetimes of the drive systems are unlimited.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In order to provide confidence and for the first investigations, an initial conversion from a conventional oil-guided turbo charger into air-guided was done.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] For a real future version, the use of results obtained from high-temperature solutions, mass products (proved production costs) and high-frequency spindles (know-how of dynamic background) will be very helpful.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In terms of the measurement of wafers and flat panels, it is very important to place the sensor chip precisely and without any contact along the surface.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Therefore, the chip is integrated directly into the bearing's surface.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] When placing the air bearing with the sensor chip, they must not touch the wafer surface being measured.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] As for the up-and-down movement, a pneumatic piston is used which is, for repeatability reasons, also air-guided.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The preload of the air bearing and thus the gap height are also adjusted with this piston.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The needed contact force for the probe is adjustable and independent from stroke.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The lift drive is based on a voice coil motor; the guidance is air-guided.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] An air-guided pneumatic piston between the chuck and the drive limits the contact force.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In particular, the air bearings are designed for lowest air consumption with the highest stiffness.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] and a flexible movement profile with high precision.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] ), which is fixed at the mirror, is manufactured of carbon fibre and carries the magnets of the linear motors.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Cables/tubes (motor, air bearing, measurement system) do not move in order to avoid breakages due to high load cycles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The air-bearings are absolutely insensitive against geometric fluctuation as a result of a temperature change.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Beside the performance, the reliability is extremely important for a production machine.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The air-guided solution is designed to be statically determined.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The iron-core linear motor and piston bearings achieve the preload for the air bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Thereby, the drive is easy to assemble and insensitive against geometric variations, for instance through temperature influences or the disposition of the machines.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Fat- and oil-free drives for respirators, stick-slip-free movements of scanners or a high rotary speed of large rotors have all been achieved with air bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] m), small weight of rotor and frame, tilt possibility of the rotor as well as a high reliability.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Besides a direct drive, a belt drive is also possible.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Primarily, stick-slip-free movements and/or smallest forces are required.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The air bearing technology is predestinated for fat/oil-free high-dynamic movements with short strokes.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] With air-guided units, optical components can be arranged to have the same diameter on a rotary table.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The air bearing with vacuum preload and a constant bearing gap height floats contact-less on top of the rotary table.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The linear slider, which is air-guided and statically determined, guarantees a high-precision positioning of the optical component before grinding.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The self-aligning process is done without friction or force.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] When clamped the component retains its position for further manufacturing in the sub-micrometer-range.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] When transporting solar panels for satellites in a launching rocket, these must be folded.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] After reaching orbit, they unfold via a spring mechanism, weightlessly and without friction.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] This process requires prior testing on Earth due to reliability reasons.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] During the testing design, the solar panels are hung on magnetic preloaded air-bearings that compensate for gravity.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] In doing so, the unfolding movement process is carried out with a minimum friction impact which means that the solar panels are tested at close to reality.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] Moreover, the design offers absolutely maintenance-free handling with equal sequential movements.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The holding force of an air bearing for one solar panel averages 600 N.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] This force is achieved by an equal distribution of the load on 16 single air bearing elements.
[src:bearing-mechanical/air-bearing] The permanent magnetic preloaded air-bearing guidance system may be used for many types of hanging transportation movements as well as for many other applications, such as for instance for the stick-slip-free positioning of components during assembly.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The special case of a rotation with an internal axis passing through the body's own center of mass is known as a **spin** (or *autorotation*).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In that case, the surface intersection of the internal *spin axis* can be called a *pole*; for example, Earth's rotation defines the geographical poles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A rotation around an axis completely external to the moving body is called a **revolution** (or **orbit**), as in a planetary orbit, e.g., Earth's orbit around the Sun.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The ends of the external *axis of revolution* can be called the *orbital poles*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Either type of rotation is involved in a corresponding type of angular velocity (spin angular velocity and orbital angular velocity) and angular momentum (spin angular momentum and orbital angular momentum).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Mathematically, a rotation is a rigid body movement which, unlike a translation, keeps at least one point fixed.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This definition applies to rotations in two dimensions (in a plane), in which exactly one point is kept fixed; and also in three dimensions (in space), in which additional points may be kept fixed (as in rotation around a fixed axis, as infinite line).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] All rigid body movements are rotations, translations, or combinations of the two.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A rotation is simply a progressive radial orientation to a common point.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] That common point lies within the axis of that motion.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The axis is perpendicular to the plane of the motion.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] If a rotation around a point or axis is followed by a second rotation around the same point/axis, a third rotation results.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The *reverse* (*inverse*) of a rotation is also a rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Thus, the rotations around a point/axis form a group.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] However, a rotation around a point or axis and a rotation around a different point/axis may result in something other than a rotation, e.g. a translation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Rotations around the *x*, *y* and *z* axes are called *principal rotations*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Rotation around any axis can be performed by taking a rotation around the *x* axis, followed by a rotation around the *y* axis, and followed by a rotation around the *z* axis.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] That is to say, any spatial rotation can be decomposed into a combination of principal rotations.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The combination of any sequence of rotations of an object in three dimensions about a fixed point is always equivalent to a rotation about an axis (which may be considered to be a rotation in the rotation plane that is perpendicular to that axis).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Similarly, the rotation rate of an object in three dimensions at any instant is about some axis, although this axis may be changing over time.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In other than three dimensions, it does not make sense to describe a rotation as being around an axis, since more than one axis through the object may be kept fixed; instead, simple rotations are described as being in a plane.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In four or more dimensions, a combination of two or more rotations about a plane is not in general a rotation in a single plane.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] 2-dimensional rotations, unlike the 3-dimensional ones, possess no axis of rotation, only a point about which the rotation occurs.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This is equivalent, for linear transformations, with saying that there is no direction in the plane which is kept unchanged by a 2-dimensional rotation, except, of course, the identity.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The question of the existence of such a direction is the question of existence of an eigenvector for the matrix *A* representing the rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Therefore, there is no real eigenvalue whenever $\cos \theta \neq \pm 1$ , meaning that no real vector in the plane is kept unchanged by *A*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Using the principal arc-cosine, this formula gives a rotation angle satisfying $0\leq \alpha \leq 180^{\circ }$ .
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The corresponding rotation axis must be defined to point in a direction that limits the rotation angle to not exceed 180 degrees.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Every proper rotation A in 3D space has an axis of rotation, which is defined such that any vector v that is aligned with the rotation axis will not be affected by rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Accordingly, $Av=v$ , and the rotation axis therefore corresponds to an eigenvector of the rotation matrix associated with an eigenvalue of 1.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] As long as the rotation angle $\alpha$ is nonzero (i.e., the rotation is not the identity tensor), there is one and only one such direction.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Because A has only real components, there is at least one real eigenvalue, and the remaining two eigenvalues must be complex conjugates of each other (see Eigenvalues and eigenvectors#Eigenvalues and the characteristic polynomial).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Knowing that 1 is an eigenvalue, it follows that the remaining two eigenvalues are complex conjugates of each other, but this does not imply that they are complex—they could be real with double multiplicity.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In the degenerate case of a rotation angle $\alpha =180^{\circ }$ , the remaining two eigenvalues are both equal to −1.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In the degenerate case of a zero rotation angle, the rotation matrix is the identity, and all three eigenvalues are 1 (which is the only case for which the rotation axis is arbitrary).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A spectral analysis is not required to find the rotation axis.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] If n denotes the unit eigenvector aligned with the rotation axis, and if $\alpha$ denotes the rotation angle, then it can be shown that $2\sin(\alpha )n=\{A_{32}-A_{23},A_{13}-A_{31},A_{21}-A_{12}\}$ .
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Consequently, the expense of an eigenvalue analysis can be avoided by simply normalizing this vector *if it has a nonzero magnitude.* On the other hand, if this vector has a zero magnitude, it means that $\sin(\alpha )=0$ .
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In other words, this vector will be zero if and only if the rotation angle is 0 or 180 degrees, and the rotation axis may be assigned in this case by normalizing any column of $A+I$ that has a nonzero magnitude.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This discussion applies to a proper rotation, and hence $\det A=1$ .
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Any improper orthogonal 3x3 matrix B may be written as $B=-A$ , in which A is proper orthogonal.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] That is, any improper orthogonal 3x3 matrix may be decomposed as a proper rotation (from which an axis of rotation can be found as described above) followed by an inversion (multiplication by −1).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] It follows that the rotation axis of A is also the eigenvector of B corresponding to an eigenvalue of −1.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] As much as every tridimensional rotation has a rotation axis, also every tridimensional rotation has a plane, which is perpendicular to the rotation axis, and which is left invariant by the rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The rotation, restricted to this plane, is an ordinary 2D rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The proof proceeds similarly to the above discussion.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] First, suppose that all eigenvalues of the 3D rotation matrix *A* are real.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This means that there is an orthogonal basis, made by the corresponding eigenvectors (which are necessarily orthogonal), over which the effect of the rotation matrix is just stretching it.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] If we write *A* in this basis, it is diagonal; but a diagonal orthogonal matrix is made of just +1s and −1s in the diagonal entries.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Therefore, we do not have a proper rotation, but either the identity or the result of a sequence of reflections.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] It follows, then, that a proper rotation has some complex eigenvalue.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Let *v* be the corresponding eigenvector.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] because, since ${\bar {v}}^{\text{T}}{\bar {v}}$ is real, it equals its complex conjugate $v^{\text{T}}v$ , and ${\bar {v}}^{\text{T}}v$ and $v^{\text{T}}{\bar {v}}$ are both representations of the same scalar product between v and ${\bar {v}}$ .
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This means $v+{\bar {v}}$ and $i(v-{\bar {v}})$ are orthogonal vectors.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Also, they are both real vectors by construction.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] These vectors span the same subspace as v and ${\bar {v}}$ , which is an invariant subspace under the application of *A*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Therefore, they span an invariant plane.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This plane is orthogonal to the invariant axis, which corresponds to the remaining eigenvector of *A*, with eigenvalue 1, because of the orthogonality of the eigenvectors of *A*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A vector is said to be rotating if it changes its orientation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This effect is generally only accompanied when its rate of change vector has non-zero perpendicular component to the original vector.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Which also gives a relation of rate of change of unit vector by taking ${\vec {A}}$ , to be such a vector: ${d{\hat {A}} \over dt}\cdot {\hat {A}}=0$ showing that ${\textstyle {d{\hat {A}} \over dt}}$ vector is perpendicular to the vector, ${\vec {A}}$ .
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] since the first term is parallel to ${\vec {A}}$ and the second perpendicular to it, we can conclude in general that the parallel and perpendicular components of rate of change of a vector independently influence only the magnitude or orientation of the vector respectively.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Hence, a rotating vector always has a non-zero perpendicular component of its rate of change vector against the vector itself.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] As dimensions increase the number of rotation vectors increases.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Along a four dimensional space (a hypervolume), rotations occur along x, y, z, and w axis.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] An object rotated on a w axis intersects through various volumes, where each intersection is equal to a self contained volume at an angle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This gives way to a new axis of rotation in a 4d hypervolume, where a 3D object can be rotated perpendicular to the z axis.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The speed of rotation is given by the angular frequency (rad/s) or frequency (turns per time), or period (seconds, days, etc.).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The time-rate of change of angular frequency is angular acceleration (rad/s2), caused by torque.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The angular velocity vector (an *axial vector*) also describes the direction of the axis of rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Similarly, the torque is an axial vector.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The physics of the rotation around a fixed axis is mathematically described with the axis–angle representation of rotations.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] According to the right-hand rule, the direction away from the observer is associated with clockwise rotation and the direction towards the observer with counterclockwise rotation, like a screw.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] It is possible for objects to have periodic circular trajectories without changing their orientation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] These types of motion are treated under circular motion instead of rotation, more specifically as a curvilinear translation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Since translation involves displacement of rigid bodies while preserving the orientation of the body, in the case of curvilinear translation, all the points have the same instantaneous velocity whereas relative motion can only be observed in motions involving rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In rotation, the orientation of the object changes and the change in orientation is independent of the observers whose frames of reference have constant relative orientation over time.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] By Euler's theorem, any change in orientation can be described by rotation about an axis through a chosen reference point.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Hence, the distinction between rotation and circular motion can be made by requiring an instantaneous axis for rotation, a line passing through instantaneous center of circle and perpendicular to the plane of motion.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In the example depicting curvilinear translation, the center of circles for the motion lie on a straight line but it is parallel to the plane of motion and hence does not resolve to an axis of rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In contrast, a rotating body will always have its instantaneous axis of zero velocity, perpendicular to the plane of motion.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] More generally, due to Chasles' theorem, any motion of rigid bodies can be treated as a composition of **rotation** and translation, called general plane motion.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A simple example of pure rotation is considered in rotation around a fixed axis.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Euler rotations provide an alternative description of a rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] It is a composition of three rotations defined as the movement obtained by changing one of the Euler angles while leaving the other two constant.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Euler rotations are never expressed in terms of the external frame, or in terms of the co-moving rotated body frame, but in a mixture.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] They constitute a mixed axes of rotation system, where the first angle moves the line of nodes around the external axis *z*, the second rotates around the line of nodes and the third one is an intrinsic rotation around an axis fixed in the body that moves.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] These rotations are called precession, nutation, and *intrinsic rotation*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A system which behaves the same regardless of how it is oriented in space is said to be rotationally invariant.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] According to Noether's theorem, if the action (the integral over time of its Lagrangian) of a physical system is invariant under rotation, then angular momentum is conserved.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In astronomy, rotation is a commonly observed phenomenon; it includes both spin (auto-rotation) and orbital revolution.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The rotation or spin of a black hole is its only astronomical property other than its mass and charge.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The rotation stores enormous amounts of energy, powering relativistic jets of ionized particles extending thousands of parsecs into space and lasting hundreds of millions of years.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The jets are strong enough to alter the evolution of galaxies.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Black holes spin much faster than neutron stars despite their similar origin in supernova, suggesting that the spinning magnetic field of the neutron star transfers rotational energy to ionized gases exiting the nova explosion.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Stars, planets and similar bodies may spin around on their axes.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The rotation rate of planets in the Solar System was first measured by tracking visual features.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Stellar rotation is measured through Doppler shift or by tracking active surface features.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] An example is sunspots, which rotate around the Sun at the same velocity as the outer gases that make up the Sun.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Under some circumstances orbiting bodies may lock their spin rotation to their orbital rotation around a larger body.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This effect is called tidal locking; the Moon is tidal-locked to the Earth.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This rotation induces a centrifugal acceleration in the reference frame of the Earth which slightly counteracts the effect of gravitation the closer one is to the equator.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Earth's gravity combines both mass effects such that an object weighs slightly less at the equator than at the poles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Another is that over time the Earth is slightly deformed into an oblate spheroid; a similar equatorial bulge develops for other planets.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Another consequence of the rotation of a planet are the phenomena of precession and nutation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Like a gyroscope, the overall effect is a slight "wobble" in the movement of the axis of a planet.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Currently the tilt of the Earth's axis to its orbital plane (obliquity of the ecliptic) is 23.44 degrees, but this angle changes slowly (over thousands of years).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Most planets in the Solar System, including Earth, spin in the same direction as they orbit the Sun.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Venus may be thought of as rotating slowly backward (or being "upside down").
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Uranus rotates nearly on its side relative to its orbit.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Current speculation is that Uranus started off with a typical prograde orientation and was knocked on its side by a large impact early in its history.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The dwarf planet Pluto (formerly considered a planet) is anomalous in several ways, including that it also rotates on its side.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] While *revolution* is often used as a synonym for *rotation*, in many fields, particularly astronomy and related fields, *revolution*, often referred to as *orbital revolution* for clarity, is used when one body moves around another while *rotation* is used to mean the movement around an axis.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Moons revolve around their planets, planets revolve about their stars (such as the Earth around the Sun); and stars slowly revolve about their galaxial centers.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The motion of the components of galaxies is complex, but it usually includes a rotation component.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In flight dynamics, the principal rotations described with Euler angles above are known as *pitch*, *roll* and *yaw*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The term rotation is also used in aviation to refer to the upward pitch (nose moves up) of an aircraft, particularly when starting the climb after takeoff.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Principal rotations have the advantage of modelling a number of physical systems such as gimbals, and joysticks, so are easily visualised, and are a very compact way of storing a rotation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] But they are difficult to use in calculations as even simple operations like combining rotations are expensive to do, and suffer from a form of gimbal lock where the angles cannot be uniquely calculated for certain rotations.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Different roughness on each side of arrow fletching produces spin in arrow-flight.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] This rotation improves the stability of the arrow in flight and the precision of the trajectory.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A Ferris wheel has a horizontal central axis, and parallel axes for each gondola, where the rotation is opposite, by gravity or mechanically.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] As a result, at any time the orientation of the gondola is upright (not rotated), just translated.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] The tip of the translation vector describes a circle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A carousel provides rotation about a vertical axis.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Many rides provide a combination of rotations about several axes.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In Chair-O-Planes the rotation about the vertical axis is provided mechanically, while the rotation about the horizontal axis is due to the centripetal force.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] In roller coaster inversions the rotation about the horizontal axis is one or more full cycles, where inertia keeps people in their seats.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Rotation of a ball or other object, usually called *spin*, plays a role in many sports, including topspin and backspin in tennis, *English*, *follow* and *draw* in billiards and pool, curve balls in baseball, spin bowling in cricket, flying disc sports, etc.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Table tennis paddles are manufactured with different surface characteristics to allow the player to impart a greater or lesser amount of spin to the ball.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Rotation of a player one or more times around a vertical axis may be called *spin* in figure skating, *twirling* (of the baton or the performer) in baton twirling, or *360*, *540*, *720*, etc. in snowboarding, etc.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Rotation of a player or performer one or more times around a horizontal axis may be called a flip, roll, somersault, *heli*, etc. in gymnastics, waterskiing, or many other sports, or a *one-and-a-half*, *two-and-a-half*, *gainer* (starting facing away from the water), etc. in diving, etc.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] A combination of vertical and horizontal rotation (back flip with 360°) is called a *möbius* in waterskiing freestyle jumping.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] Rotation of a player around a vertical axis, generally between 180 and 360 degrees, may be called a *spin move* and is used as a deceptive or avoidance manoeuvre, or in an attempt to play, pass, or receive a ball or puck, etc., or to afford a player a view of the goal or other players.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axis-of-rotation] It is often seen in hockey, basketball, football of various codes, tennis, etc.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] An **axle** or **axletree** is a central shaft for a rotating wheel or gear.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] On wheeled vehicles, the axle may be fixed to the wheels, rotating with them, or fixed to the vehicle, with the wheels rotating around the axle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In the former case, bearings or bushings are provided at the mounting points where the axle is supported.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In the latter case, a bearing or bushing sits inside a central hole in the wheel to allow the wheel or gear to rotate around the axle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Sometimes, especially on bicycles, the latter type of axle is referred to as a *spindle*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] On cars and trucks, several senses of the word *axle* occur in casual usage, referring to the shaft itself, its housing, or simply any transverse pair of wheels.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Strictly speaking, a shaft that rotates with the wheel, being either bolted or splined in fixed relation to it, is called an *axle* or *axle shaft*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] However, in looser usage, an entire assembly including the surrounding axle housing (typically a casting) is also called an *axle*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] An even broader (somewhat figurative) sense of the word refers to every pair of parallel wheels on opposite sides of a vehicle, regardless of their mechanical connection to each other and to the vehicle frame or body.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Thus, transverse pairs of wheels in an independent suspension may be called an *axle* in some contexts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] This very loose definition of "axle" is often used in assessing toll roads or vehicle taxes, and is taken as a rough proxy for the overall weight-bearing capacity of a vehicle, and its potential for causing wear or damage to roadway surfaces.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Axles are an integral component of most practical wheeled vehicles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The solid axles (housings) in this system must also bear the weight of the vehicle plus any cargo.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] A non-driving axle, such as the front beam axle in heavy-duty trucks and some two-wheel drive light trucks and vans, will have no shaft, and serves only as a suspension and steering component.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Conversely, many front-wheel drive cars have a one-piece rear beam axle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In other types of suspension systems, the axles serve only to transmit driving torque to the wheels: the position and angle of the wheel hubs is made independent from the axles by the function of the suspension system.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] This is typical of the independent suspensions found on most newer cars, and even SUVs, and on the front of many light trucks.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] An exception to this rule is the independent (rear) swing axle suspension, wherein the half-axles are also load-bearing suspension arms.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Independent drive-trains still need differentials (or diffs), but without fixed axle-housing tubes attached.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The diff may be attached to the vehicle frame or body, and/or be integrated with the transmission (or gearbox) in a combined transaxle unit.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The axle (half-)shafts then transmit driving torque to the wheels, usually via constant-velocity joints.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Like a full floating axle system, the drive shafts in a front-wheel-drive independent suspension system do not support any vehicle weight.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] A straight axle is a single rigid shaft connecting a wheel on the left side of the vehicle to a wheel on the right side.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The axis of rotation fixed by the axle is common to both wheels.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Such a design can keep the wheel positions steady under heavy stress, and can therefore support heavy loads.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Straight axles are used on trains (that is, locomotives and railway wagons), for the rear axles of commercial trucks, and on heavy-duty off-road vehicles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The axle can optionally be protected and further reinforced by enclosing the length of the axle in a housing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In split-axle designs, the wheel on each side is attached to a separate shaft.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Modern passenger cars have split-drive axles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In some designs, this allows independent suspension of the left and right wheels, and therefore a smoother ride.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Even when the suspension is not independent, split axles permit the use of a differential, allowing the left and right drive wheels to be driven at different speeds as the automobile turns, improving traction and extending tire life.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] A tandem axle is a group of two or more axles situated close together.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Truck designs use such a configuration to provide a greater weight capacity than a single axle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Semi-trailers usually have a tandem axle at the rear.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Axles are typically made from SAE grade 41xx steel or SAE grade 10xx steel.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] SAE grade 41xx steel is commonly known as "chrome-molybdenum steel" (or "chrome-moly") while SAE grade 10xx steel is known as "carbon steel".
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The primary differences between the two are that chrome-moly steel is significantly more resistant to bending or breaking, and is very difficult to weld with tools normally found outside a professional welding shop.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] An axle that is driven by the engine or prime mover is called a *drive axle*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Modern front-wheel drive cars typically combine the transmission (gearbox and differential) and front axle into a single unit called a *transaxle*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The drive axle is a split axle with a differential and universal joints between the two half axles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Each half axle connects to the wheel by use of a constant velocity (CV) joint which allows the wheel assembly to move freely vertically as well as to pivot when making turns.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In rear-wheel drive cars and trucks, the engine turns a driveshaft (also called a *propeller shaft* or *tailshaft*) which transmits the rotational force to a drive axle at the rear of the vehicle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The drive axle may be a live axle, but modern rear-wheel drive automobiles generally use a split axle with a differential.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In this case, one half-axle or half-shaft connects the differential with the left rear wheel, a second half-shaft does the same with the right rear wheel; thus the two half-axles and the differential constitute the rear axle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The front drive axle is providing the force to drive the truck.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In fact, only one wheel of that axle is actually moving the truck and trailer down the road.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Some simple vehicle designs, such as leisure go-karts, may have a single driven wheel where the drive axle is a split axle with only one of the two shafts driven by the engine, or else have both wheels connected to one shaft without a differential (kart racing).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] However, other go-karts have two rear drive wheels too.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Some dump trucks and trailers may be configured with a lift axle (also known as an *airlift axle* or *drop axle*), which may be mechanically raised or lowered.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The axle is lowered to increase the weight capacity, or to distribute the weight of the cargo over more wheels, for example, to cross a weight-restricted bridge.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] When not needed, the axle is lifted off the ground to save wear on the tires and axle, and to increase traction in the remaining wheels, and to decrease fuel consumption.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Lifting an axle also alleviates lateral scrubbing of the additional axle in very tight turns, allowing the vehicle to turn more readily.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In some situations, the removal of pressure from the additional axle is necessary for the vehicle to complete a turn at all.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Several manufacturers offer computer-controlled airlifts so that the dead axles are automatically lowered when the main axle reaches its weight limit.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The dead axles can still be lifted by the press of a button if needed, for better maneuverability.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Lift axles were in use in the early 1940s.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Initially, the axle was lifted by a mechanical device.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Soon hydraulics replaced the mechanical lift system.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] One of the early manufacturers was Zetterbergs, located in Östervåla, Sweden.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The liftable tandem drive axle was invented in 1957 by the Finnish truck manufacturer Vanajan Autotehdas, a company sharing history with Sisu Auto.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] A full-floating axle carries the vehicle's weight on the axle casing, not the half-shafts; they serve only to transmit torque from the differential to the wheels.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] They "float" inside an assembly that carries the vehicle's weight.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Thus the only stress it must endure is torque (not lateral bending force).
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Full-floating axle shafts are retained by a flange bolted to the hub, while the hub and bearings are retained on the spindle by a large nut.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] In contrast, a semi-floating design carries the weight of the vehicle on the axle shaft itself; there is a single bearing at the end of the axle housing that carries the load from the axle and that the axle rotates through.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] To be "semi-floating" the axle shafts must be able to "float" in the housing, bearings and seals, and not subject to axial "thrust" and/or bearing preload.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] A true semi-floating axle assembly places no side loads on the axle housing tubes or axle shafts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] Axles that are pressed into ball or tapered roller bearings, which are in turn retained in the axle housings with flanges, bolts, and nuts do not "float" and place axial loads on the bearings, housings, and only a short section of the shaft itself, that also carries all radial loads.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The full-floating design is typically used in most ¾- and 1-ton light trucks, medium-duty trucks, and heavy-duty trucks.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The overall assembly can carry more weight than a semi-floating or non-floating axle assembly because the hubs have two bearings riding on a fixed spindle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] A full-floating axle can be identified by a protruding hub to which the axle shaft flange is bolted.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The semi-floating axle setup is commonly used on half-ton and lighter 4×4 trucks in the rear.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] This setup allows the axle shaft to be the means of propulsion, and also support the weight of the vehicle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The main difference between the full- and semi-floating axle setups is the number of bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The semi-floating axle features only one bearing, while the full-floating assembly has bearings on both the inside and outside of the wheel hub.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] To remove the semi-floating axle, the wheel must be removed first; if such an axle breaks, the wheel is most likely to come off the vehicle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] The semi-floating design is found under most ½-ton and lighter trucks, as well as in SUVs and rear-wheel-drive passenger cars, usually being smaller or less expensive models.
[src:bearing-mechanical/axle] A benefit of a full-floating axle is that even if an axle shaft (used to transmit torque or power) breaks, the wheel will not come off, preventing serious accidents.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The original Babbitt alloy was invented in 1839 by Isaac Babbitt in Taunton, Massachusetts, United States.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] He disclosed one of his alloy recipes but kept others as trade secrets.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Other formulations were developed later.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Like other terms whose eponymous origin is long-since deemphasized (such as *diesel engine* or *eustachian tube*), the term *babbitt metal* is frequently styled in lowercase.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] It is preferred over the term "white metal", because that term refers to zinc die-casting metal, to lead-based alloys and to tin-based alloys, in addition to bearing metal.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Babbitt metal is most commonly used as a thin surface layer in a complex, multi-metal assembly, but its original use was as a cast-in-place bulk bearing material.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Babbitt metal is characterized by its resistance to galling.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Babbitt metal is soft and easily damaged, which suggests that it might be unsuitable for a bearing surface; however, its structure is made up of small, hard crystals dispersed in a softer metal, which makes it, technically, a metal matrix composite.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] As the bearing wears, the softer metal erodes somewhat, creating paths for lubricant between the hard high spots that provide the actual bearing surface.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] When tin is used as the softer metal, friction causes the tin to melt and function as a lubricant, protecting the bearing from wear when other lubricants are absent.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Internal combustion engines use Babbitt metal which is primarily tin-based because it can withstand cyclic loading.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] In the traditional style of a babbitt-metal bearing, a cast-iron pillow block is assembled as a loose fit around the shaft, with the shaft in its approximate final position.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The inner face of the cast-iron pillow block is often drilled to form a key to locate the bearing metal as it is cast into place.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The shaft is coated with soot as a release agent, the ends of the bearing are packed with clay to form a mold, and molten metal is poured into the cavity around the shaft, initially filling the lower half of the pillow block.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The bearing is stripped, and the metal trimmed back to the top surface of the pillow block.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Solidified babbitt metal is soft enough to be cut with a knife or sharp chisel.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] A steel shim is inserted to protect the face of the lower bearing and to space the cap of the pillow block away from the shaft.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] After resealing the ends with clay, more metal is then poured to fill the cap of the pillow block through the hole in the top of the pillow-block cap, which will eventually become a lubrication port.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The two halves of the bearing are then split at the shim, the shim removed, the oil holes cleared of metal, and oil ways cut into the surface of the new bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The shaft is smeared with engineer's blue and rotated in the bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] When the bearing is disassembled, the blue fills the hollows and is rubbed off the high spots, making them visible.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The high spots are scraped down, and the process repeated, until a uniform and evenly distributed pattern of blue shows when the shaft is removed.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The bearing is then cleaned and lubricated, and shimmed up so that the shaft is held firmly but not binding in the bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The bearing is then "run in" by being run heavily lubricated at low load and slow revolution, completing the process of exposing the hard bearing surface.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] After final adjustment of the shimming, a very reliable and high-load-capability bearing results.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Before the advent of low-cost electric motors, power was distributed through factories from a central engine via overhead shafts running in hundreds of Babbitt bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Often, leather, fabric or rubber belts would be used to transfer this rotating power to working machines.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The expression a "run bearing" also derives from this style of bearing, since failure of lubrication will lead to heat build-up due to friction in the bearing, eventually leading to the bearing metal melting and running out of the pillow block.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Until the mid-1950s, poured Babbitt bearings were common in automotive applications.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The Babbitt was poured into the block or caps using a form.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Tin-based Babbitts were used, as they could stand up to the impact loads found on the connecting rods and crankshaft.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The poured Babbitt bearings were kept thin.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The rods and caps would have shims that could be peeled off as the Babbitt wore down.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Ford was known to use two 0.002" on each cap and Babbitt that was 86% tin, 7% copper, and 7% antimony (see the KRW catalogs for the Model T).
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Steel shims were used, as the brass shims used today tend to compress over time, contributing to shorter bearing life.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The poured Babbitt bearings commonly get over 50,000 miles of use before needing replacement.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Poured Babbitt bearings are also known to fail gracefully, allowing the car to be driven for extended periods of time.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The failed bearing is not likely to damage the crankshaft.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The crankshaft and connecting-rod big-end bearings in current automobile engines are made of a replaceable steel shell, keyed to the bearing caps.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The inner surface of the steel shell is plated with a coating of bronze, which is in turn coated with a thin layer of Babbitt metal as the bearing surface.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The process of laying down this layer of metal is known as Babbitting.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] In many applications, rolling-element bearings, such as ball or roller bearings, have replaced Babbitt bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Though such bearings can offer a lower coefficient of friction than plain bearings, their key advantage is that they can operate reliably without a continuous pressurized supply of lubricant.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Ball and roller bearings can also be used in configurations that are required to carry both radial and axial thrusts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] However, rolling-element bearings lack the beneficial damping and shock-load capability provided by fluid-film bearings, such as the Babbitt.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Johnson's apparent elastic limit is taken as the unit stress at the point where the slope of the tangent to the curve is 2/3 times its slope in origin.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] In addition to ASTM B23 grades, the British Standard BS 3332:1987 specifies chemical compositions for eight white metal bearing alloys in ingot form, including four tin-based (e.g., BS 3332:1987 Alloy A) and four lead-based (e.g., BS 3332:1987 Alloy G) variants used for casting plain bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] These standards ensure controlled impurity levels for fatigue resistance and embeddability in high-load applications like engines and turbines.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] The engineering of a bearing's Babbitt lining is usually completed during the design of the machine.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] In selecting the proper type of Babbitt for a particular job, there are a number of factors to take into consideration, the most important of which are the surface speed of the shaft and the load that the bearing is required to carry.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] If a bearing is to be highly loaded in relation to its size, then a high-tin alloy is desirable, whereas for much lower-speed work and less heavily loaded bearings, a lead-based Babbitt may be employed and is far more economical.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Load bearing is required to carry (the weight which is being exerted through the combined weights of the shaft and any other direct weights on the shaft and measured in pounds-force per square inch): **Formula**: *L* = *W* / (I.D × L.O.B.).
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] For example, a bearing in continuous use in a harsh environment without regular maintenance will require different Babbitt and lubrication than a bearing in intermittent use in a clean, light-duty environment.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] This process is essentially the culmination of the technician's expertise and the experience gained from rebuilding the bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] If the bearing has performed well in use over many years, then the bearing needs simply to be rebuilt to its original specification and formulation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Load bearing surface preparation and finish.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] Eco-Babbitt is an alloy of 90% Sn, 7% Zn, 3% Cu that is not technically a Babbitt metal.
[src:bearing-mechanical/babbitt-metal] See Solder alloys for more information on Eco-Babbitt.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] A **bearing** is a machine element that constrains relative motion to only the desired motion and reduces friction between moving parts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The design of the bearing may, for example, provide for free linear movement of the moving part or for free rotation around a fixed axis; or, it may prevent a motion by controlling the vectors of normal forces that bear on the moving parts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Most bearings facilitate the desired motion by minimizing friction.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearings are classified broadly according to the type of operation, the motions allowed, or the directions of the loads (forces) applied to the parts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The term "bearing" is derived from the verb "to bear"; a bearing being a machine element that allows one part to bear (i.e., to support) another.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The simplest bearings are bearing surfaces, cut or formed into a part, with varying degrees of control over the form, size, roughness, and location of the surface.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Other bearings are separate devices installed into a machine or machine part.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The most sophisticated bearings for the most demanding applications are very precise components; their manufacture requires some of the highest standards of current technology.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Rotary bearings hold rotating components such as shafts or axles within mechanical systems and transfer axial and radial loads from the source of the load to the structure supporting it.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The simplest form of bearing, the *plain bearing*, consists of a shaft rotating in a hole.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Lubricants come in different forms, including liquids, solids, and gases.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The choice of lubricant depends on the specific application and factors such as temperature, load, and speed.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] In the *ball bearing* and *roller bearing*, to reduce sliding friction, rolling elements such as rollers or balls with a circular cross-section are located between the races or journals of the bearing assembly.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] A wide variety of bearing designs exists to allow the demands of the application to be correctly met for maximum efficiency, reliability, durability, and performance.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] There is no archaeological evidence for this sequence of technological development.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The Egyptian drawings in the tomb of Djehutihotep are believed to show the process of moving massive stone blocks not with rollers but upon sledges pulled over sand which was wetted to increase its cohesion and reduce friction.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] There are also Egyptian drawings of plain bearings used to support the far end of hand drills.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Wheeled vehicles using plain bearings emerged between about 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] A recovered example of an early rolling-element bearing is a wooden ball bearing supporting a rotating table from the remains of the Roman Nemi ships in Lake Nemi, Italy.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Leonardo da Vinci incorporated drawings of ball bearings in his design for a helicopter around the year 1500; this is the first recorded use of bearings in an aerospace design.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] However, Agostino Ramelli is the first to have published roller and thrust bearings sketches.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] An issue with the ball and roller bearings is that the balls or rollers rub against each other, causing additional friction.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] This can be reduced by enclosing each individual ball or roller within a cage.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The captured, or caged, ball bearing was originally described by Galileo in the 17th century.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The first practical caged-roller bearing was invented in the mid-1740s by horologist John Harrison for his H3 marine timekeeper.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] In this timepiece, the caged bearing was only used for a very limited oscillating motion, but later on, Harrison applied a similar bearing design with a true rotational movement in a contemporaneous regulator clock.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The first patent on ball bearings was awarded to Philip Vaughan, a Welsh inventor and ironmaster in Carmarthen in 1794.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] His was the first modern ball-bearing design, with the ball running along a groove in the axle assembly.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearings played a pivotal role in the nascent Industrial Revolution, allowing the new industrial machinery to operate efficiently.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] For example, they were used for holding wheel and axle assemblies to greatly reduce friction compared to prior non-bearing designs.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The first patent for a radial-style ball bearing was awarded to Jules Suriray, a Parisian bicycle mechanic, on 3 August 1869.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The bearings were then fitted to the winning bicycle ridden by James Moore in the world's first bicycle road race, Paris-Rouen, in November 1869.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] In 1883, Friedrich Fischer, founder of FAG, developed an approach for milling and grinding balls of equal size and exact roundness by means of a suitable production machine, which set the stage for the creation of an independent bearing industry.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] His hometown Schweinfurt later became a world-leading center for ball bearing production.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The modern, self-aligning design of ball bearing is attributed to Sven Wingquist of the SKF ball-bearing manufacturer in 1907 when he was awarded Swedish patent No.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Henry Timken, a 19th-century visionary and innovator in carriage manufacturing, patented the tapered roller bearing in 1898.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The following year he formed a company to produce his innovation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Over a century, the company grew to make bearings of all types, including specialty steel bearings and an array of related products and services.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Erich Franke invented and patented the wire race bearing in 1934.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] His focus was on a bearing design with a cross-section as small as possible and which could be integrated into the enclosing design.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] After World War II, he founded with Gerhard Heydrich the company Franke & Heydrich KG (today Franke GmbH) to push the development and production of wire race bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Richard Stribeck's extensive research on ball bearing steels identified the metallurgy of the commonly used 100Cr6 (AISI 52100), showing coefficient of friction as a function of pressure.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Designed in 1968 and later patented in 1972, Bishop-Wisecarver's co-founder Bud Wisecarver created vee groove bearing guide wheels, a type of linear motion bearing consisting of both an external and internal 90-degree vee angle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] In the early 1980s, Pacific Bearing's founder, Robert Schroeder, invented the first bi-material plain bearing that was interchangeable with linear ball bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] This bearing had a metal shell (aluminum, steel or stainless steel) and a layer of Teflon-based material connected by a thin adhesive layer.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Today's ball and roller bearings are used in many applications, which include a rotating component.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Examples include ultra high-speed bearings in dental drills, aerospace bearings in the Mars Rover, gearbox and wheel bearings on automobiles, flexure bearings in optical alignment systems, and air bearings used in coordinate-measuring machines.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The first plain and rolling-element bearings were wood, closely followed by bronze.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Over their history, bearings have been made of many materials, including ceramic, sapphire, glass, steel, bronze, and other metals.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Plastic bearings made of nylon, polyoxymethylene, polytetrafluoroethylene, and UHMWPE, among other materials, are also in use today.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Watchmakers produce "jeweled" watches using sapphire plain bearings to reduce friction, thus allowing more precise timekeeping.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Even basic materials can have impressive durability.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Wooden bearings, for instance, can still be seen today in old clocks or in water mills where the water provides cooling and lubrication.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] By far, the most common bearing is the plain bearing, a bearing that uses surfaces in rubbing contact, often with a lubricant such as oil or graphite.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] A plain bearing may or may not be a discrete device.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] With suitable lubrication, plain bearings often give acceptable accuracy, life, and friction at minimal cost.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] However, there are many applications where a more suitable bearing can improve efficiency, accuracy, service intervals, reliability, speed of operation, size, weight, and costs of purchasing and operating machinery.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Thus, many types of bearings have varying shapes, materials, lubrication, principle of operation, and so on.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The following table summarizes the notable characteristics of each of these bearing types.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Reducing friction in bearings is often important for efficiency, to reduce wear and to facilitate extended use at high speeds and to avoid overheating and premature failure of the bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Essentially, a bearing can reduce friction by virtue of its shape, by its material, or by introducing and containing a fluid between surfaces or by separating the surfaces with an electromagnetic field.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Combinations of these can even be employed within the same bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] An example is where the cage is made of plastic, and it separates the rollers/balls, which reduce friction by their shape and finish.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearing design varies depending on the size and directions of the forces required to support.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Forces can be predominately radial, axial (thrust bearings), or bending moments perpendicular to the main axis.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Different bearing types have different operating speed limits.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Speed is typically specified as maximum relative surface speeds, often specified ft/s or m/s.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Rotational bearings typically describe performance in terms of the product *DN* where *D* is the mean diameter (often in mm) of the bearing and *N* is the rotation rate in revolutions per minute.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Generally, there is considerable speed range overlap between bearing types.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Plain bearings typically handle only lower speeds, rolling element bearings are faster, followed by fluid bearings and finally magnetic bearings which are limited ultimately by centripetal force overcoming material strength.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Some applications apply bearing loads from varying directions and accept only limited play or "slop" as the applied load changes.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] One source of motion is gaps or "play" in the bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] For example, a 10 mm shaft in a 12 mm hole has 2 mm play.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Allowable play varies greatly depending on the use.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] As an example, a wheelbarrow wheel supports radial and axial loads.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Axial loads may be hundreds of newtons force left or right, and it is typically acceptable for the wheel to wobble by as much as 10 mm under the varying load.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] In contrast, a lathe may position a cutting tool to ±0.002 mm using a ball lead screw held by rotating bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Stiffness is the amount that the gap varies when the load on the bearing changes, distinct from the friction of the bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] A second source of motion is elasticity in the bearing itself.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] For example, the balls in a ball bearing are like stiff rubber and under load deform from a round to a slightly flattened shape.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The race is also elastic and develops a slight dent where the ball presses on it.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The stiffness of a bearing is how the distance between the parts separated by the bearing varies with the applied load.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] With rolling element bearings, this is due to the strain of the ball and race.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] With fluid bearings, it is due to how the pressure of the fluid varies with the gap (when correctly loaded, fluid bearings are typically stiffer than rolling element bearings).
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Some bearings use a thick grease for lubrication, which is pushed into the gaps between the bearing surfaces, also known as *packing*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The grease is held in place by a plastic, leather, or rubber gasket (also called a *gland*) that covers the inside and outside edges of the bearing race to keep the grease from escaping.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearings may also be packed with other materials.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Historically, the wheels on railroad cars used sleeve bearings packed with *waste* or loose scraps of cotton or wool fiber soaked in oil, then later used solid pads of cotton.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearings can be lubricated by a ring oiler, a metal ring that rides loosely on the central rotating shaft of the bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The ring hangs down into a chamber containing lubricating oil.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] As the bearing rotates, viscous adhesion draws oil up the ring and onto the shaft, where the oil migrates into the bearing to lubricate it.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Excess oil is flung off and collects in the pool again.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] A rudimentary form of lubrication is splash lubrication.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Some machines contain a pool of lubricant in the bottom, with gears partially immersed in the liquid, or crank rods that can swing down into the pool as the device operates.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The spinning wheels fling oil into the air around them, while the crank rods slap at the surface of the oil, splashing it randomly on the engine's interior surfaces.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Some small internal combustion engines specifically contain special plastic *flinger wheels* which randomly scatter oil around the interior of the mechanism.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] For high-speed and high-power machines, a loss of lubricant can result in rapid bearing heating and damage due to friction.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Also, in dirty environments, the oil can become contaminated with dust or debris, increasing friction.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] In these applications, a fresh supply of lubricant can be continuously supplied to the bearing and all other contact surfaces, and the excess can be collected for filtration, cooling, and possibly reuse.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Pressure oiling is commonly used in large and complex internal combustion engines in parts of the engine where directly splashed oil cannot reach, such as up into overhead valve assemblies.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] High-speed turbochargers also typically require a pressurized oil system to cool the bearings and keep them from burning up due to the heat from the turbine.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Composite bearings are designed with a self-lubricating polytetrafluorethylene (PTFE) liner with a laminated metal backing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The PTFE liner offers consistent, controlled friction as well as durability, whilst the metal backing ensures the composite bearing is robust and capable of withstanding high loads and stresses throughout its long life.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Its design also makes it lightweight-one tenth the weight of a traditional rolling element bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] There are many methods of mounting bearings, usually involving an interference fit.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] When press fitting or shrink fitting a bearing into a bore or onto a shaft, it's important to keep the housing bore and shaft outer diameter to very close limits, which can involve one or more counterboring operations, several facing operations, and drilling, tapping, and threading operations.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Alternatively, an interference fit can also be achieved with the addition of a tolerance ring.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The service life of the bearing is affected by many factors not controlled by the bearing manufacturers.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] For example, bearing mounting, temperature, exposure to external environment, lubricant cleanliness, and electrical currents through bearings.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] High frequency PWM inverters can induce electric currents in a bearing, which can be suppressed by the use of ferrite chokes.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The temperature and terrain of the micro-surface will determine the amount of friction by touching solid parts.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Certain elements and fields reduce friction while increasing speeds.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Strength and mobility help determine the load the bearing type can carry.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Alignment factors can play a damaging role in wear and tear, yet overcome by computer aid signaling and non-rubbing bearing types, such as magnetic levitation or air field pressure.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Fluid and magnetic bearings can have practically indefinite service lives.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] In practice, fluid bearings support high loads in hydroelectric plants that have been in nearly continuous service since about 1900 and show no signs of wear.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Rolling element bearing life is determined by load, temperature, maintenance, lubrication, material defects, contamination, handling, installation and other factors.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] These factors can all have a significant effect on bearing life.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearing life is statistical: several samples of a given bearing will often exhibit a bell curve of service life, with a few samples showing significantly better or worse life.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearing life varies because microscopic structure and contamination vary greatly even where macroscopically they seem identical.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The L10/B10 life of the bearing is theoretical, and may not represent service life of the bearing.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearings are also rated using the C0 (static loading) value.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] This is the basic load rating as a reference, and not an actual load value.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] For plain bearings, some materials give a much longer life than others.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Some of the John Harrison clocks still operate after hundreds of years because of the *lignum vitae* wood employed in their construction, whereas his metal clocks are seldom run due to potential wear.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Flexure bearings rely on elastic properties of a material.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Flexure bearings bend a piece of material repeatedly.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Some materials fail after repeated bending, even at low loads, but careful material selection and bearing design can make flexure bearing life indefinite.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Although long bearing life is often desirable, it is sometimes not necessary.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Harris 2001 describes a bearing for a rocket motor oxygen pump that gave several hours life, far in excess of the several tens of minutes needed.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Depending on the customized specifications (backing material and PTFE compounds), composite bearings can operate up to 30 years without maintenance.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] For bearings which are used in oscillating applications, customized approaches to calculate L10/B10 are used.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Many bearings require periodic maintenance to prevent premature failure, but others require little maintenance.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The latter include various kinds of polymer, fluid and magnetic bearings, as well as rolling-element bearings that are described with terms including *sealed bearing* and *sealed for life*.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] These contain seals to keep the dirt out and the grease in.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] They work successfully in many applications, providing maintenance-free operation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Some applications cannot use them effectively.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Nonsealed bearings often have a grease fitting, for periodic lubrication with a grease gun, or an oil cup for periodic filling with oil.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Before the 1970s, sealed bearings were not encountered on most machinery, and oiling and greasing were a more common activity than they are today.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] For example, automotive chassis used to require "lube jobs" nearly as often as engine oil changes, but today's car chassis are mostly sealed for life.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] From the late 1700s through the mid-1900s, industry relied on many workers called oilers to lubricate machinery frequently with oil cans.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Factory machines today usually have *lube systems*, in which a central pump serves periodic charges of oil or grease from a reservoir through *lube lines* to the various *lube points* in the machine's bearing surfaces, bearing journals, pillow blocks, and so on.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The timing and number of such *lube cycles* is controlled by the machine's computerized control, such as PLC or CNC, as well as by manual override functions when occasionally needed.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] This automated process is how all modern CNC machine tools and many other factory machines are lubricated.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Similar lube systems are also used on nonautomated machines, in which case there is a hand pump that a machine operator is supposed to pump once daily (for machines in constant use) or once weekly.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] These are called *one-shot systems* from their chief selling point: one pull on one handle to lube the whole machine, instead of a dozen pumps of an alemite gun or oil can in a dozen different positions around the machine.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The oiling system inside a modern automotive or truck engine is similar in concept to the lube systems mentioned above, except that oil is pumped continuously.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Much of this oil flows through passages drilled or cast into the engine block and cylinder heads, escaping through ports directly onto bearings and squirting elsewhere to provide an oil bath.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The oil pump simply pumps constantly, and any excess pumped oil continuously escapes through a relief valve back into the sump.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Many bearings in high-cycle industrial operations need periodic lubrication and cleaning, and many require occasional adjustment, such as pre-load adjustment, to minimize the effects of wear.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Bearing life is often much better when the bearing is kept clean and well-lubricated.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] However, many applications make good maintenance difficult.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] One example is bearings in the conveyor of a rock crusher are exposed continually to hard abrasive particles.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Cleaning is of little use because cleaning is expensive, yet the bearing is contaminated again as soon as the conveyor resumes operation.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Thus, a good maintenance program might lubricate the bearings frequently but not include any disassembly for cleaning.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] The frequent lubrication, by its nature, provides a limited kind of cleaning action by displacing older (grit-filled) oil or grease with a fresh charge, which itself collects grit before being displaced by the next cycle.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] Another example are bearings in wind turbines, which makes maintenance difficult since the nacelle is placed high up in the air in strong wind areas.
[src:bearing-mechanical/bearing-mechanical] In addition, the turbine does not always run and is subjected to different operating behavior in different weather conditions, which makes proper lubrication a challenge.
